🗂️ Tabs
Tabs are the primary navigation elements in Salesforce. They appear at the top of every app and are managed by users (in-app) and Admins (via Setup).
TypeDescriptionExampleStandardDefault tabs created by SalesforceAccounts, ContactsCustomCreated by Admin for Custom ObjectsStudent__c, Order__cWebEmbeds an external website inside Salesforcegoogle.comVisualforceDisplays a custom page built by a developerCustom UI pagesLightning ComponentOpens a Lightning ComponentCustom App Pages

⚠️ Important: Custom Objects are not visible in any App unless a Custom Tab is created for them.

Tab Visibility Options (per Profile)

Default ON — Tab is visible automatically
Default OFF — Tab exists but the user must enable it manually
Hidden — Tab is not visible to that profile

How to Create Tabs (Setup → Quick Find → "Tabs")

Custom Tab → Choose Object → Choose Style → Set Profile visibility → Assign to Apps → Save
Web Tab → Choose layout → Give Label → Enter URL → Set visibility → Save
Visualforce Tab → Choose VF Page → Give Label → Set visibility → Save
Lightning Component Tab → Choose Component → Give Label → Set visibility → Save


📦 Apps
Apps are collections of tabs grouped together for a specific business purpose. Accessible from the App Launcher (9 dots, top-left).
Types of Apps
1. Standard Apps

Pre-built by Salesforce (Sales, Service, Marketing)
Cannot be deleted — only hidden
Tabs can be added or removed

2. Custom Apps

Created by Admins for specific business teams
Can be created, edited, and deleted
Example: HR App → HR Team → Employee__c, Payroll__c

3. Connected Apps

Connect third-party tools to Salesforce via OAuth 2.0
No password sharing — a token is generated instead
Example: Google Workspace, Microsoft Teams

4. Packaged Apps

Installed from AppExchange (Salesforce's marketplace)
Managed Package — Code is locked/protected
Unmanaged Package — Code is open and editable


🔐 OAuth 2.0 — How It Works
User → Clicks Connect → Third-Party App → Asks Permission
→ User Approves → Token Generated → Secure Access Granted
OAuth 2.0 is a secure way to give an external app permission to access your Salesforce data without sharing your password.

🛠️ Creating Apps
Custom App (Setup → App Manager → New Lightning App)

Give App Details — Name, Description, Logo, Style
Set App Options — Navigation, Form Factor
Add Utility Bar (optional)
Add Navigation Items (tabs)
Assign User Profiles and set visibility:

Visible — App appears in their App Launcher
Default ON — App opens automatically on login
Not assigned → Profile cannot see the app



Connected App (Setup → App Manager → New External Client App)

Give Name (API Name auto-generates) and Email
Enable OAuth Settings
Set Callback URL and OAuth Scopes
Save and verify under External Client Apps

Packaged App (AppExchange)

Visit appexchange.salesforce.com
Search and click Get it Now
Log in with Salesforce credentials
Choose: Admins Only / All Users / Specific Profiles
Install → Approve → Continue
Verify under Setup → Installed Packages


💡 Key Takeaways

A Custom Object is invisible in any app without a corresponding Custom Tab
Standard Apps can be hidden but never deleted
OAuth 2.0 enables secure third-party integrations without password sharing
AppExchange is Salesforce's equivalent of an app marketplace — with managed (locked) and unmanaged (editable) packages


